'''Ingrid Christensen Kildegaard''' (died September 2, 1984 in [[Haines Falls, New York]]) was an American [[statistician]] and [[market research]]er who worked at the [[Advertising Research Foundation]] as a vice president and technical director.{{r|nyt}}

Kildegaard graduated from [[Central Michigan University]] (Michigan State Teachers College) in 1936.{{r|centralight|minn}} She did her graduate studies at the [[University of Minnesota]], completing a master's degree in statistics there in 1950.{{r|nyt|minn|mincon}} She joined the Advertising Research Foundation in 1956 and was promoted to Director of Technical Services in 1965.{{r|rostworowski}} At around that time, she became involved in discussions with the [[United States Census Bureau]] over whether they should survey ownership of advanced [[television]] sets capable of color and of receiving [[UHF]] signals.{{r|census}}
In 1970 she served as chair of the Subsection on Statistics in Marketing of the [[American Statistical Association]].{{r|subsection}}
She retired in 1982.{{r|nyt}}

In 1967, she was elected as a [[Fellow of the American Statistical Association]].{{r|fasa}}
The Market Research Council added her to their Hall of Fame in 2007.{{r|hall}}

